  "text": "Because changes in the opiate system were noted during pregnancy, it was assumed that the endogenous opiates helped regulate fetal development. During late pregnancy, concentrations of Met-enkephalin and Met-enkephalin-Arg6-Phe 7 increased in the plasma of fetal sheep, but the total amount of Met-enkephalin-containing peptides did not change, possibly reflecting changes in the synthesis and/or secretion of enkephalin peptides within sympathetic nerves as parturition neared [CITATION_1] . Levels of gene expression of enkephalin precursors changed in the brain during pregnancy, with POMC mRNA in the arcuate nucleus decreasing at parturition. Preproenkephalin mRNA in the ventromedial nucleus decreased during late pregnancy and parturition, but in the paraventricular nucleus, it rose at parturition after declining at the end of pregnancy [CITATION_2] .",
